        },
        "text_Pk87iU": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>I run warm and almost always prefer lighter layers next to skin with something packable on top. After four years riding year-round in Vermont, and now dealing with the Bay’s microclimates. I’ve learned that starting slightly cool works best. Most days I keep it simple: breathable layer next to skin, light insulation if needed, and a vest or shell I can stash mid-ride. It’s a system that works from foggy summer mornings to long spring climbs.</p>",
            "text_font_size": "body-medium",
            "padding_bottom": 16
          }
        },
